The paper deals with the problem of linear regression in high-dimensional settings, which is a fundamental problem in machine learning and statistics. The paper proposes a new approach called Principal Component Regression (PCR) and analyzes its robustness to noisy, sparse, and mixed-valued covariates. This makes cs.LG (Machine Learning) the most likely category. The paper also involves statistical analysis and estimation, which suggests cs.ST (Statistics) as the second likely category. The paper proposes a data-driven approach to select the number of components, which involves optimization and decision-making, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a likely category. The paper also involves matrix estimation and completion, which suggests cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as a likely category. Finally, the paper involves the analysis of error bounds, which suggests cs.IT (Information Theory) as a possible category.
